The best approach for `File.*` and `Directory.*` is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already covers all three calls.

**1. Install:**
```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

**2. Register in DI:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// MockFileSystem automatically creates parent directories

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.True(manager.DirectoryExists("/data"));
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/data/config.json"));

manager.Save("/data/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/out.txt"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?** `System.IO.Abstractions` covers the entire `System.IO` surface — `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `Stream`, etc. — so you won't need to expand your interface every time you use a new file operation. The `MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory filesystem out of the box, no mocking framework needed.

Once installed, you can use the **`migrate-static-to-wrapper`** skill to bulk-replace existing `File.*`/`Directory.*` call sites across your project.
